<h2>Overview (TL;DR)</h2>

<p>One of Phreesia's core products requires patients to check in for their medical appointments online before they're seen. They move through a lengthy intake form covering their health history, insurance, and reason for visit. At the very end, they're asked to opt into personalized marketing campaigns. Some were doing it without realizing it, and the targeted ads that followed felt eerie enough that people started posting about it on social media. The company asked me to represent the UX design perspective on a large cross-functional team brought together to fix the consent form. There was one constraint: opt-in rates couldn't drop. Optimizing for conversion while making the form genuinely transparent are goals that pull against each other. What shipped was a shorter form with slightly clearer language, not the structural changes that could have made a real difference. I ended the project knowing how I'd make the case differently next time.</p>

<h2>Problem</h2>

<p>The marketing opt-in form sat at the end of a lengthy digital check-in flow, at the point where patient fatigue is highest. It was written in dense legal language, required multiple scrolls to reach the checkbox, and was visually indistinguishable from the clinical consent forms that preceded it. Patients checked the opt-in box without reading the page, causing confusion about why advertisements felt so personal and intrusive. The company wanted to address this, but executives made clear that any change risking lower opt-in rates was off the table. Each opt-in translated directly to advertising revenue.</p>

