<h2>Process</h2>

<p>Before proposing any solutions, I ran comprehension testing to establish a baseline. Participants were asked to read the marketing opt-in form and explain in their own words what they were agreeing to. Most couldn't, even when they tried to read the legal text carefully. That finding confirmed the problem was real and gave the project a clear direction.</p>

<p>From there I ran a heat map study where participants clicked or tapped words and phrases they found confusing. It generated a clear picture of which language was causing the most friction, and gave me concrete targets for revision.</p>

<p>The harder part was testing solutions. I ran a fatigue simulation, a check-in flow long enough to mimic what patients actually experience before reaching the opt-in form, and tested several approaches within it: breaking up the dense paragraphs, increasing font size, and adding plain-language callouts that summarized each section in clearer terms. None performed with statistical significance over the others. That became a recurring challenge. Leadership was already skeptical of the UserZoom platform itself, questioning whether compensated participants engaged thoughtfully enough to produce credible data. Combined with a preference for statistically significant findings, a standard that qualitative UX research isn't designed to meet, meant the findings were easy to set aside.</p>

