<p>One study tested a concept the COO had brought to the table: interactive popovers, borrowed from Google's privacy pages, that would let patients select a term and read a plain-language explanation. I ran the study because the idea deserved a full investigation, even though I suspected the added interaction wouldn't move the needle. It didn't.</p>

<p>The data scientists on the team were running A/B tests in parallel throughout, testing changes as granular as punctuation and capitalization. I pushed back on this approach. That level of detail made sense: the team wanted to be able to attribute any movement in opt-in rates to a specific change, but delayed our fix.</p>

<p>By the time changes were ready to evaluate, the business was already satisfied with the A/B test results coming out of beta, so I didn't run post-change comprehension testing. The project had been long, my findings had repeatedly failed to move the room, and I was burning out. It's the part of the process I'd most want to close differently, because we never found out whether patients actually understood the form any better than they had before.</p>

<h2>Solution</h2>

<p>What shipped was a condensed version of the marketing opt-in form. It required fewer scrolls to reach the checkbox and used language the team believed to be clearer than the original. Opt-in rates remained stable. From the company's perspective, the project was a success.</p>

<blockquote class="pull-quote" role="note">
  <p>"Patients were still being asked to make a consequential decision at the most fatigued point in a long form, in language designed to protect the business rather than inform the user."</p>
</blockquote>

<p>From the patient's perspective, I'm less sure. The changes may have reduced some friction but didn't address the root problem. Patients were still being asked to make a consequential decision at the most fatigued point in a long form, in language designed to protect the business rather than inform the user.</p>

<h2>Reflection</h2>

<p>I took this project on as the most senior-level designer on my team, but I was by far the most junior person on this task force. If I could go back, I would build alliances earlier. Lone advocacy in a room that senior rarely moves anything. One person from Legal worried about liability, or a product leader with patient trust on their roadmap, could have shifted the dynamic so that I wasn't the only one advocating for the user.</p>

<p>I also should have recognized the tension of the project sooner. The changes most likely to help patients understand what they were agreeing to were also the most likely to reduce opt-ins. The solution was always going to be how much change the business could afford to make without losing revenue.</p>

<p>The argument that might have landed wasn't a design argument. The social media complaints were already a reputational risk. Another cycle of them would have been a revenue risk too. I didn't make that case, and I should have.</p>

<p>This project taught me that design advocacy without business framing is just opinion. I came in with the right instincts about what patients needed. What I didn't have yet was the fluency to make that case in a room where revenue was the primary language.</p>